# Introduction

Consider this code.

```jsx
useEffect(() => {

    console.log("Hello");

}, []);
```

Why does it run only once?

Why not every render?

The answer lies in

```
Dependency Arrays
```

---

# React's Question

Every time your component renders,

React asks

```
Did any dependency change?
```

If the answer is

```
Yes
```

↓

Run the effect.

Otherwise

↓

Skip it.

---

# Three Forms

## Form 1

```jsx
useEffect(() => {

    console.log("Runs");

});
```

Runs

```
Every Render
```

---

## Form 2

```jsx
useEffect(() => {

    console.log("Runs");

}, []);
```

Runs

```
Only Once
```

(after mounting)

---

## Form 3

```jsx
useEffect(() => {

    console.log(count);

}, [count]);
```

Runs

```
Mount

↓

Whenever count changes
```

---

# Example

```jsx
const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
const [name, setName] = useState("Utpal");

useEffect(() => {

    console.log("Effect");

}, [count]);
```

Suppose

```
count changes
```

Effect runs.

---

Suppose

```
name changes
```

Effect does NOT run.

Because

```
name

is not

a dependency.
```

---

# Visual

```
Dependencies

↓

[count]

↓

count changed?

↓

YES

↓

Run Effect

↓

NO

↓

Skip
```

---

# How React Compares Dependencies

React compares

the previous dependency

with

the new dependency.

Think of it like

```javascript
oldValue === newValue
```

If the values are equal,

the effect is skipped.

If they are different,

the effect runs.

---

# Primitive Values

Example

```jsx
const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
```

Previous

```
0
```

New

```
1
```

React sees

```
0 !== 1
```

↓

Run effect.

---

# Objects

Now consider

```jsx
const user = {

    name: "Utpal"

};
```

Even if the contents look identical,

creating a new object means

```javascript
{} !== {}
```

because they are different object references.

---

# Example

```jsx
const user = {

    name: "Utpal"

};

useEffect(() => {

    console.log("User changed");

}, [user]);
```

Every render

creates

a new object.

React thinks

```
New Object

↓

Changed
```

So

the effect runs every render.

---

# Arrays

Exactly the same.

```jsx
const numbers = [1,2,3];
```

Each render

creates

a new array.

React sees

```
New Array

↓

Changed
```

Effect runs again.

---

# Functions

Functions are objects too.

```jsx
function greet(){

}
```

Every render

creates

a new function object.

Therefore

```jsx
useEffect(() => {

}, [greet]);
```

runs every render.

Later

we'll solve this using

```
useCallback()
```

---

# Infinite Loop Example

```jsx
const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

useEffect(() => {

    setCount(count + 1);

}, [count]);
```

What happens?

```
count changes

↓

Effect runs

↓

setCount()

↓

Render

↓

count changes

↓

Effect runs

↓

Forever
```

Infinite loop.

---

# Correct Version

Suppose

you want

to initialize count.

```jsx
useEffect(() => {

    setCount(10);

}, []);
```

Runs

only once.

---

# Stale Closures

Consider

```jsx
const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

useEffect(() => {

    console.log(count);

}, []);
```

Question

Will it print

updated values?

No.

It always sees

the value from

the first render.

This is called

```
Stale Closure
```

---

# Why?
 
Because the effect never runs again.

It "captures" the variables from the initial render.

---

# Fix

```jsx
useEffect(() => {

    console.log(count);

}, [count]);
```

Now

the effect

receives

the latest value.

---

# ESLint Warning

Suppose

```jsx
useEffect(() => {

    console.log(count);

}, []);
```

Many React projects

show

```
React Hook useEffect

has a missing dependency

'count'
```

This warning exists because

the effect uses `count`

but React won't re-run it when `count` changes.

---

# Should You Ignore It?

Usually No.

The warning often points to a real bug.

Sometimes you intentionally want the first value only, but that should be a deliberate choice.

---

# Real Example

ResearchMind AI

```text
Open Chat

↓

Fetch Chat History

↓

Display Messages
```

Correct

```jsx
useEffect(() => {

    fetchChats();

}, []);
```

Runs once.

---

Now suppose

conversation ID changes.

```text
Conversation A

↓

Conversation B
```

We should fetch again.

```jsx
useEffect(() => {

    fetchChats();

}, [conversationId]);
```

Now changing the conversation loads the correct messages.

---

# Best Practices

✅ Include every value that the effect uses unless you intentionally want otherwise.

---

✅ Keep dependency arrays small and meaningful.

---

✅ Don't put newly created objects or functions directly into dependency arrays unless you understand their behavior.

---

# Common Mistakes

❌

Missing dependencies.

---

❌

Adding objects that change every render.

---

❌

Calling setState() inside an effect that depends on that same state without a stopping condition.

