# 3 – Fetching Data with useEffect()

---

# 🎯 Learning Objectives

By the end of this lesson, you will understand:

- How to fetch data from an API
- Why API calls belong inside `useEffect()`
- How to use `async/await` with `useEffect()`
- Loading state
- Error state
- Rendering fetched data
- How to connect to a FastAPI backend

---

# The Problem

Suppose you want to display GitHub user information.

Where should the API call go?

❌ Wrong

```jsx
function App() {

    const response = await fetch(...);

    return <div>Hello</div>;

}
```

Problems:

- `await` can't be used directly here.
- The component function would execute on every render.
- Multiple unnecessary requests would be made.

---

# Correct Flow

```text
Component Mounts
        │
        ▼
Render Initial UI
        │
        ▼
useEffect Runs
        │
        ▼
Fetch Data
        │
        ▼
Update State
        │
        ▼
Component Re-renders
        │
        ▼
Display Data
```

---

# Step 1 — Create State

```jsx
const [user, setUser] = useState(null);
```

Initially

```
user = null
```

---

# Step 2 — Loading State

```jsx
const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
```

Initially

```
loading = true
```

---

# Step 3 — Error State

```jsx
const [error, setError] = useState(null);
```

Initially

```
error = null
```

---

# Step 4 — Fetch Data

```jsx
useEffect(() => {

    async function fetchUser() {

        try {

            const response = await fetch(
                "https://api.github.com/users/octocat"
            );

            const data = await response.json();

            setUser(data);

        }

        catch (err) {

            setError(err.message);

        }

        finally {

            setLoading(false);

        }

    }

    fetchUser();

}, []);
```

Notice

The async function is **inside** `useEffect()`.

---

# Why Not This?

```jsx
useEffect(async () => {

});
```

React expects the callback to return either:

- nothing (`undefined`)
- or a cleanup function.

An `async` function always returns a Promise.

That's why React recommends wrapping async logic inside the effect instead of making the effect callback itself async.

---

# Rendering

```jsx
if (loading) {

    return <h2>Loading...</h2>;

}

if (error) {

    return <h2>{error}</h2>;

}

return (

    <div>

        <h1>{user.name}</h1>

    </div>

);
```

---

# Complete Example

```jsx
import { useEffect, useState } from "react";

function App() {

    const [user, setUser] = useState(null);

    const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);

    const [error, setError] = useState(null);

    useEffect(() => {

        async function fetchUser() {

            try {

                const response = await fetch(
                    "https://api.github.com/users/octocat"
                );

                if (!response.ok) {

                    throw new Error("Request failed");

                }

                const data = await response.json();

                setUser(data);

            }

            catch (err) {

                setError(err.message);

            }

            finally {

                setLoading(false);

            }

        }

        fetchUser();

    }, []);

    if (loading) {

        return <h2>Loading...</h2>;

    }

    if (error) {

        return <h2>{error}</h2>;

    }

    return (

        <div>

            <img
                src={user.avatar_url}
                alt={user.login}
                width="150"
            />

            <h2>{user.name}</h2>

            <p>{user.bio}</p>

        </div>

    );

}

export default App;
```

---

# What Happens Internally?

```text
App Mounts
      │
      ▼
loading = true
user = null
      │
      ▼
Loading... appears
      │
      ▼
useEffect runs
      │
      ▼
fetch()
      │
      ▼
Server responds
      │
      ▼
setUser(data)
setLoading(false)
      │
      ▼
React re-renders
      │
      ▼
User information appears
```

---

# Why Three States?

Instead of trying to handle everything with one variable, we separate concerns.

```text
user

↓

Stores data
```

```text
loading

↓

Shows spinner/message
```

```text
error

↓

Displays failures
```

This makes the UI predictable and easy to understand.

---

# Connecting to FastAPI

Suppose your backend is running on

```text
http://localhost:8000
```

and exposes

```text
GET /users
```

Then the fetch call becomes

```jsx
const response = await fetch(
    "http://localhost:8000/users"
);
```

Everything else remains the same.

React doesn't care whether the API is GitHub, Weather API, or your own FastAPI service—as long as it returns JSON.

---

# Common Mistakes

❌ Calling `fetch()` directly in the component body.

❌ Forgetting to handle loading.

❌ Forgetting to handle errors.

❌ Assuming every response is successful.

Always check:

```jsx
if (!response.ok) {

    throw new Error("Request failed");

}
```

---

# Best Practices

✅ Use `try/catch`.

✅ Use `async/await`.

✅ Show loading indicators.

✅ Handle errors gracefully.

✅ Keep API calls inside `useEffect()` when they should happen after rendering.

