# 4 – Cleanup Functions & Preventing Memory Leaks

---

# 🎯 Learning Objectives

By the end of this lesson, you will understand:

- What a cleanup function is
- When React calls cleanup
- Cleaning up timers
- Cleaning up event listeners
- Aborting API requests
- Cleaning up WebSocket connections
- Preventing memory leaks

---

# Introduction

Imagine opening a page that starts a timer.

```jsx
setInterval(() => {

    console.log("Running...");

}, 1000);
```

Now you navigate away from the page.

Question:

Does the timer automatically stop?

No.

Unless you stop it yourself, it keeps running.

That's why React provides cleanup functions.

---

# What is a Cleanup Function?

A cleanup function is simply a function returned from `useEffect()`.

```jsx
useEffect(() => {

    // setup work

    return () => {

        // cleanup work

    };

}, []);
```

The returned function tells React how to clean up the resources created by the effect.

---

# When Does Cleanup Run?

Cleanup runs in two situations:

1. Before the effect runs again (if dependencies changed)
2. When the component unmounts

---

# Visual

```text
Mount
    │
    ▼
Run Effect
    │
    ▼
User Changes Dependency
    │
    ▼
Cleanup Previous Effect
    │
    ▼
Run New Effect
    │
    ▼
Component Unmounts
    │
    ▼
Final Cleanup
```

---

# Example 1 — Timer

Without cleanup

```jsx
useEffect(() => {

    setInterval(() => {

        console.log("Tick");

    }, 1000);

}, []);
```

Problem

The timer continues forever.

---

Correct

```jsx
useEffect(() => {

    const id = setInterval(() => {

        console.log("Tick");

    }, 1000);

    return () => {

        clearInterval(id);

    };

}, []);
```

---

Visual

```text
Mount

↓

Start Timer

↓

User Leaves Page

↓

clearInterval()

↓

Timer Stops
```

---

# Example 2 — Event Listener

Suppose

```jsx
window.addEventListener(
    "resize",
    handleResize
);
```

If you don't remove it,

each mount adds another listener.

Eventually

```
Resize

↓

handleResize()

↓

handleResize()

↓

handleResize()
```

The same event fires multiple times.

---

Correct

```jsx
useEffect(() => {

    window.addEventListener(
        "resize",
        handleResize
    );

    return () => {

        window.removeEventListener(
            "resize",
            handleResize
        );

    };

}, []);
```

---

# Example 3 — Fetch Requests

Suppose

the user opens a page

and immediately leaves it.

The request may still finish.

If it tries to update state

after the component has gone,

that work is unnecessary.

One common solution is using an `AbortController`.

```jsx
useEffect(() => {

    const controller = new AbortController();

    async function load() {

        try {

            const response = await fetch(
                "/users",
                {
                    signal: controller.signal
                }
            );

            const data = await response.json();

            setUsers(data);

        }

        catch (err) {

            if (err.name !== "AbortError") {

                console.error(err);

            }

        }

    }

    load();

    return () => {

        controller.abort();

    };

}, []);
```

---

# Example 4 — WebSocket

Imagine your ResearchMind AI chat.

When the page opens

```
Connect WebSocket
```

When the page closes

```
Disconnect WebSocket
```

```jsx
useEffect(() => {

    const socket = new WebSocket(url);

    return () => {

        socket.close();

    };

}, []);
```

---

# Why Cleanup Matters

Without cleanup

```text
Open Page

↓

Timer Running

↓

Close Page

↓

Timer Still Running
```

After opening and closing the page five times

```text
Timer 1

Timer 2

Timer 3

Timer 4

Timer 5
```

All are running simultaneously.

---

# React Lifecycle with Cleanup

```text
Mount

↓

Run Effect

↓

Update

↓

Cleanup Previous Effect

↓

Run New Effect

↓

Unmount

↓

Final Cleanup
```

Notice that cleanup happens **before** React runs the next version of the effect, not just when the component disappears.

---

# What Doesn't Need Cleanup?

Some effects don't create ongoing resources.

Example

```jsx
useEffect(() => {

    document.title = "Dashboard";

}, []);
```

Nothing needs to be cleaned up.

Simply updating the document title doesn't create a timer, listener, or connection.

---

# Common Mistakes

❌ Forgetting `clearInterval()`.

❌ Forgetting `removeEventListener()`.

❌ Leaving WebSockets open.

❌ Ignoring request cancellation in long-running fetches.

---

# Best Practices

✅ Clean up anything you create.

✅ Always remove event listeners.

✅ Stop timers.

✅ Close sockets.

✅ Abort fetches when appropriate.

---

# Hands-on Exercise

Create

```jsx
function Clock() {

    useEffect(() => {

        const id = setInterval(() => {

            console.log("Tick");

        }, 1000);

        return () => {

            clearInterval(id);

        };

    }, []);

    return <h1>Clock</h1>;

}
```

Now conditionally render it:

```jsx
{
    showClock && <Clock />
}
```

Toggle `showClock`.

Observe that the timer stops when the component unmounts.

