# Key Takeaways

- Cleanup functions are returned from `useEffect()`.
- React runs cleanup before re-running an effect and when a component unmounts.
- Timers, event listeners, WebSockets, and long-running requests should usually be cleaned up.
- Proper cleanup prevents memory leaks and unnecessary work.

---

# Summary

Cleanup functions are an essential part of writing reliable React applications. Whenever an effect creates something that continues running outside React—such as a timer, event listener, network connection, or subscription—you should usually provide a cleanup function to stop or remove it. This keeps your application efficient and prevents subtle bugs.

