# 5 – useRef()

---

# 🎯 Objectives

- What `useRef()` is
- Why React provides `useRef()`
- Accessing DOM elements
- Persisting values across renders
- Difference between `useState()` and `useRef()`
- Common use cases
- Best practices

---

# Introduction

Suppose you have an input box.

When the page loads,

you want the cursor to automatically appear inside it.

How can React directly access that HTML element?

That's exactly what `useRef()` is for.

---

# What is useRef()?

`useRef()` creates an object that survives across renders.

```jsx
const inputRef = useRef(null);
```

It returns

```jsx
{
    current: null
}
```

React keeps this object the same between renders.

---

# Visual

```text
Component

↓

useRef()

↓

{

    current: ...

}
```

Whenever React re-renders,

the object stays the same.

Only

```
current
```

can change.

---

# Basic Syntax

```jsx
import { useRef } from "react";

const inputRef = useRef(null);
```

---

# Connecting a Ref

```jsx
<input ref={inputRef} />
```

React stores

the actual DOM element

inside

```jsx
inputRef.current
```

---

# Visual

```text
inputRef

↓

current

↓

<input>
```

---

# Auto Focus Example

```jsx
import { useEffect, useRef } from "react";

function App() {

    const inputRef = useRef(null);

    useEffect(() => {

        inputRef.current.focus();

    }, []);

    return (

        <input

            ref={inputRef}

            placeholder="Enter name"

        />

    );

}
```

---

# What Happens?

```
Component Mounts

↓

React Creates Input

↓

Stores DOM Element

↓

inputRef.current

↓

useEffect()

↓

focus()

↓

Cursor Appears
```

---

# Reading Input Value

```jsx
const inputRef = useRef(null);

function handleClick(){

    console.log(

        inputRef.current.value

    );

}
```

React gives

direct access

to the DOM element.

---

# useState vs useRef

Suppose

```jsx
const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
```

Updating

```
count
```

causes

```
Re-render
```

---

Now

```jsx
const countRef = useRef(0);

countRef.current++;
```

Updates

```
current
```

Only.

No re-render occurs.

---

# Comparison

| useState | useRef |
|-----------|---------|
| Stores state | Stores mutable value |
| Causes re-render | Does NOT cause re-render |
| Used for UI data | Used for values or DOM references |
| React tracks changes | React ignores changes to `.current` |

---

# Example

```jsx
const countRef = useRef(0);

function handleClick(){

    countRef.current++;

    console.log(

        countRef.current

    );

}
```

The console changes

```
1

2

3
```

But

the screen

does not update.

---

# Why?

React only re-renders

when

state

or

props

change.

Changing

```jsx
ref.current
```

doesn't tell React

to render again.

---

# Persisting Values

Suppose

you want to count

how many times

the component rendered.

```jsx
const renderCount = useRef(0);

renderCount.current++;

console.log(renderCount.current);
```

The value persists

between renders

without creating

another render.

---

# Real Example

Imagine

ResearchMind AI

```text
User Types Question

↓

Current Input Element

↓

Focus Input

↓

Continue Typing
```

The input element itself

is a perfect use case

for `useRef()`.

---

# Another Example

Video Player

```jsx
const videoRef = useRef(null);

function play(){

    videoRef.current.play();

}

function pause(){

    videoRef.current.pause();

}
```

---

# Common Mistakes

❌

Using `useRef`

for UI state.

Example

```jsx
ref.current = "Hello";
```

If the UI should display `"Hello"`,

use `useState()` instead.

---

❌

Reading

`ref.current`

before the element exists.

Remember

it is `null`

until React mounts the element.

---

# Best Practices

✅ Use refs for DOM elements.

✅ Use refs for timers, IDs, or mutable values that don't affect rendering.

✅ Use state for anything the user should see on the screen.

---

# Hands-on Exercise

Create

```jsx
function App(){

    const inputRef = useRef(null);

    function focusInput(){

        inputRef.current.focus();

    }

    return(

        <>

            <input ref={inputRef} />

            <button

                onClick={focusInput}

            >

                Focus Input

            </button>

        </>

    );

}
```

Click the button.

The cursor should move

into the input field.

