# 7 – React.memo() & useCallback()

---

# 🎯 Objectives

- Why child components re-render
- What `React.memo()` does
- What `useCallback()` does
- Function identity
- Why inline functions cause unnecessary renders
- How `useMemo()`, `useCallback()`, and `React.memo()` work together

---

# Introduction

Consider this component.

```jsx
function Parent(){

    const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

    return (

        <>

            <button
                onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}
            >
                Increment
            </button>

            <Child/>

        </>

    );

}
```

Click the button.

Question:

Did `Child` re-render?

Yes.

Even though

nothing inside `Child`

changed.

---

# Why?

Remember

Whenever

Parent

renders,

React executes

```jsx
Parent()
```

again.

While rendering Parent,

React also renders

its children.

---

Visual

```text
State Changes

↓

Parent Renders

↓

Child Renders
```

---

# Example

```jsx
function Child(){

    console.log("Child Render");

    return <h1>Child</h1>;

}
```

Click the button.

Console

```
Child Render

Child Render

Child Render
```

even though

Child has no state.

---

# React.memo()

React provides

```
React.memo()
```

to skip unnecessary

child renders.

---

Syntax

```jsx
const Child = React.memo(

    function Child(){

        return <h1>Child</h1>;

    }

);
```

Now React compares

the child's props.

If they didn't change,

React skips rendering.

---

# Visual

Without React.memo()

```text
Parent Render

↓

Child Render
```

---

With React.memo()

```text
Parent Render

↓

Props Changed?

↓

NO

↓

Skip Child Render
```

---

# But There's a Problem

Suppose

```jsx
function Parent(){

    const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

    function greet(){

        console.log("Hello");

    }

    return (

        <Child

            greet={greet}

        />

    );

}
```

Even though

the function code

never changes,

Child

still re-renders.

---

# Why?

Every render

creates

a new function.

Example

Render 1

```jsx
greet
```

↓

Memory

```
0x100
```

Render 2

```jsx
greet
```

↓

Memory

```
0x250
```

Different references.

React thinks

```
New Prop
```

↓

Render Child.

---

# React.memo() Comparison

React compares props.

```text
Old greet

↓

0x100

New greet

↓

0x250
```

Not equal.

Child renders again.

---

# React's Solution

```
useCallback()
```

---

# What is useCallback()?

It remembers

a function

between renders.

---

Syntax

```jsx
const greet = useCallback(

    () => {

        console.log("Hello");

    },

    []

);
```

Now

React reuses

the same function

until dependencies change.

---

# Visual

Without useCallback()

```text
Render

↓

Create Function

↓

Render

↓

Create New Function

↓

Render

↓

Create New Function
```

---

With useCallback()

```text
Render

↓

Create Function

↓

Store

↓

Reuse

↓

Reuse

↓

Reuse
```

---

# Complete Example

```jsx
const Child = React.memo(

    function Child({

        greet

    }){

        console.log(

            "Child Render"

        );

        return (

            <button

                onClick={greet}

            >

                Greet

            </button>

        );

    }

);
```

Parent

```jsx
function Parent(){

    const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

    const greet = useCallback(

        () => {

            console.log("Hello");

        },

        []

    );

    return(

        <>

            <button

                onClick={()=>

                    setCount(count+1)

                }

            >

                Increment

            </button>

            <Child

                greet={greet}

            />

        </>

    );

}
```

Now

Click

Increment.

Child

does NOT

re-render.

---

# useMemo() vs useCallback()

Remember

```
useMemo()

↓

Caches

Values
```

Example

```jsx
const total = useMemo(

    ()=>calculate(),

    []

);
```

---

```
useCallback()

↓

Caches

Functions
```

Example

```jsx
const handleClick = useCallback(

    ()=>{

    },

    []

);
```

---

# React.memo()

Caches

Components

```text
Props Changed?

↓

YES

↓

Render

↓

NO

↓

Skip
```

---

# The Three Together

```text
State Changes

↓

Parent Render

↓

React.memo()

↓

Props Same?

↓

YES

↓

Skip Child
```

Function prop

↓

Stable because of

```
useCallback()
```

Expensive value

↓

Cached by

```
useMemo()
```

---

# Common Mistakes

❌ Wrapping every component in `React.memo()`.

It has a comparison cost.

If the component is tiny,

the comparison may cost more than rendering.

---

❌ Wrapping every function in `useCallback()`.

It also has overhead.

Use it when a stable function reference is beneficial, especially for memoized children or dependency arrays.

---

❌ Thinking `React.memo()` blocks all renders.

It only skips renders

when props haven't changed.

State changes inside the memoized component will still trigger re-renders.

---

# Best Practices

✅ Use `React.memo()` for components that render often and receive the same props.

✅ Use `useCallback()` when passing callbacks to memoized child components.

✅ Use `useMemo()` for expensive computations.

Measure performance before optimizing.

---

# Hands-on Exercise

Create

Parent

```jsx
const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
```

Create

Child

```jsx
console.log(

"Child Render"

);
```

First

without

`React.memo()`.

Observe

Child renders

every click.

Now

add

`React.memo()`.

Then

pass

an inline callback.

Observe

Child renders again.

Finally

replace it with

`useCallback()`.

Observe

Child stops re-rendering.

