# Introduction

Suppose your application looks like this.

```text
App

│

├── Dashboard

│      │

│      └── Sidebar

│              │

│              └── Profile

│                      │

│                      └── Avatar
```

The user's name is stored in

```
App
```

But

```
Avatar
```

needs it.

How do we pass it?

---

# Traditional Way

```text
App

↓

Dashboard

↓

Sidebar

↓

Profile

↓

Avatar
```

Each component

passes the prop

to the next one.

Even if

it doesn't use it.

---

# Example

```jsx
<App user={user}>

↓

<Dashboard user={user}>

↓

<Sidebar user={user}>

↓

<Profile user={user}>

↓

<Avatar user={user}>
```

Only

```
Avatar
```

needs

```
user
```

The other components

just forward it.

---

# This Problem is Called

```
Prop Drilling
```

---

# Why is Prop Drilling Bad?

Imagine

10 levels

of components.

Every level

must receive

and pass

the prop.

Adding or removing a component

often means updating

many files.

---

# React's Solution

```
Context API
```

Instead of passing data

through every level,

React provides

a shared data source.

Any component

can read it.

---

# Visual

Without Context

```text
App

↓

Dashboard

↓

Sidebar

↓

Profile

↓

Avatar
```

---

With Context

```text
        Context

           ▲

           │

App

│

├── Dashboard

│

├── Sidebar

│

├── Profile

│

└── Avatar
```

Every component

can access

Context directly.

---

# Step 1 — Create Context

```jsx
import {

    createContext

} from "react";

const UserContext = createContext();
```

This creates

a context object.

---

# Step 2 — Provide Data

```jsx
<UserContext.Provider

    value={user}

>

    <App/>

</UserContext.Provider>
```

The Provider

makes data available

to all children.

---

# Step 3 — Consume Data

```jsx
import {

    useContext

