# Introduction

Suppose you have

```
User Page

Product Page

Orders Page
```

All three pages need to

- Fetch data
- Show loading
- Show errors

You write the same code three times.

```jsx
const [data, setData] = useState(null);

const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);

const [error, setError] = useState(null);

useEffect(() => {

    ...

}, []);
```

This is code duplication.

---

# React's Solution

Instead of copying the code,

move it into

```
Custom Hook
```

Then every component

can reuse it.

---

# What is a Custom Hook?

A Custom Hook is simply

```
A JavaScript function

that uses React Hooks.
```

Example

```jsx
function useSomething(){

    const [value, setValue] = useState();

    return value;

}
```

Notice

the name starts with

```
use
```

This is required by convention and enables React's Hook rules.

---

# Why "use"?

React recognizes

functions beginning with

```
use
```

as Hooks.

Good

```jsx
useFetch()

useTheme()

useAuth()
```

Bad

```jsx
fetchData()

theme()

auth()
```

---

# Example

Suppose

three components

need

```
Current Window Width
```

Without a custom hook

each component

contains

```jsx
useEffect()

↓

addEventListener()

↓

cleanup
```

Repeated three times.

---

# Create

useWindowWidth()

```jsx
import {

    useEffect,

    useState

} from "react";

function useWindowWidth(){

    const [width, setWidth] = useState(

        window.innerWidth

    );

    useEffect(() => {

        function handleResize(){

            setWidth(

                window.innerWidth

            );

        }

        window.addEventListener(

            "resize",

            handleResize

        );

        return () => {

            window.removeEventListener(

                "resize",

                handleResize

            );

        };

    }, []);

    return width;

}
```

---

# Use It

```jsx
function App(){

    const width =

        useWindowWidth();

    return(

        <h1>

            {width}

        </h1>

    );

}
```

Very clean.

---

# Example 2

useFetch()

```jsx
function useFetch(url){

    const [data, setData] = useState(null);

    const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);

    const [error, setError] = useState(null);

    useEffect(() => {

        async function load(){

            try{

                const response = await fetch(url);

                if(!response.ok){

                    throw new Error("Request failed");

                }

                const result = await response.json();

                setData(result);

            }

            catch(err){

                setError(err.message);

            }

            finally{

                setLoading(false);

            }

        }

        load();

    }, [url]);

    return {

        data,

        loading,

        error

    };

}
```

---

# Using useFetch()

```jsx
function App(){

    const {

        data,

        loading,

        error

    } = useFetch(

        "https://api.github.com/users/octocat"

    );

    if(loading){

        return <h2>Loading...</h2>;

    }

    if(error){

        return <h2>{error}</h2>;

    }

    return(

        <h1>

            {data.name}

        </h1>

    );

}
```

Notice

No `useEffect()`

inside App.

The hook hides

all the complexity.

---

# Example 3

useLocalStorage()

```jsx
function useLocalStorage(key, initialValue){

    const [value, setValue] = useState(() => {

        const stored = localStorage.getItem(key);

        return stored

            ? JSON.parse(stored)

            : initialValue;

    });

    useEffect(() => {

        localStorage.setItem(

            key,

            JSON.stringify(value)

        );

    }, [key, value]);

    return [

        value,

        setValue

    ];

}
```

---

# Using It

```jsx
const [

theme,

setTheme

] = useLocalStorage(

    "theme",

    "light"

);
```

The theme now

survives page refreshes.

---

